var definitions = ['<h2>Tu és meu irmão.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and is used in informal situations.</div><div><strong>és</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese meaning "my". It indicates ownership or relationship and agrees in gender with the noun it modifies, which is masculine singular in this case.</div><div><strong>irmão</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "brother". It stands as the object of the sentence, the person to whom the speaker is referring to as their brother.</div>','<h2>Tu comes um biscoito.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when speaking informally to one person. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>comes</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "comer", which means "to eat". It describes an action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is an indefinite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "a" in English. It’s used here before a masculine singular noun.</div><div><strong>biscoito</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "cookie" or "biscuit". It is a masculine singular noun that is the object of the verb "comes".</div>','<h2>Tu trabalhas no escritório.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing someone in an informal way. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>trabalhas</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "trabalhar", which means "to work". It indicates the action that the subject is performing.</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "o" (the), equivalent to "in the" or "at the" in English. It’s used here to indicate the location where the action of working is taking place.</div><div><strong>escritório</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "office". It is the place where the subject is working.</div>','<h2>Tu pulas muito alto.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence. In this context, it is used in an informal way, addressing someone the speaker is familiar with.</div><div><strong>pulas</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "pular", which means "to jump" in English. It indicates the action performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese meaning "very" or "much" in English. It is used to intensify or modify the verb "pulas", indicating the extent or degree of the action.</div><div><strong>alto</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese meaning "high" in English. It describes how the subject jumps, working together with "muito" to emphasize the height of the jump.</div>','<h2>Você é minha mãe.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the Portuguese subject pronoun for "you" in both singular and informal form. It can also be used formally depending on the context.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be".</div><div><strong>minha</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese feminine singular form, meaning "my". It denotes possession and it agrees in gender and number with the noun it qualifies, in this case, "mãe" (mother).</div><div><strong>mãe</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "mother". It is in the feminine singular form.</div>','<h2>Você nada na piscina todos os dias.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>nada</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "nadar", which means "to swim". Here, it’s conjugated to match the subject "você".</div><div><strong>na</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "a" (the), translating to "in the" in English. In Portuguese, contractions are very common and are used to show the relationship between words, in this case, indicating the location where the action takes place.</div><div><strong>piscina</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "pool". It’s the place where the action of swimming is taking place.</div><div><strong>todos os dias</strong> This is a Portuguese phrase meaning "every day". The word "todos" means "every/all", "os" is the definite article "the", and "dias" is the plural of "dia", which means "day". Together, they indicate the frequency of the action.</div>','<h2>Você faz muitas perguntas.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s an informal way of addressing someone directly and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>faz</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "fazer", which means "to do" or "to make". Here, it agrees with the second-person pronoun "você". In Portuguese, the verb form for "você" often matches the third-person singular.</div><div><strong>muitas</strong> This is a plural form of the Portuguese word for "many" or "much", used before feminine plural nouns. It emphasizes the quantity of nouns mentioned in the sentence.</div><div><strong>perguntas</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "pergunta", which means "question". It is a feminine noun in Portuguese, and the quantity is specified by "muitas", therefore it refers to many questions.</div>','<h2>Você pega a bola.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>pega</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "pegar", which means "to grab" or "to catch". In this instance, aligned with "Você", it translates to "you grab/catch".</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>bola</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "ball". It’s a feminine singular noun, hence it’s preceded by "a".</div>','<h2>O senhor é meu chefe.</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes masculine singular nouns.</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a form of respectful address in Portuguese, equivalent to "sir" or "Mr". in English. It’s used here to refer respectfully to the person being addressed.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates ownership or association with the speaker.</div><div><strong>chefe</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "boss" or "chief". It refers to the person that the speaker is addressing as their superior or leader in a workplace context.</div>','<h2>A senhora mora em Porto?</h2><div><strong>A</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article for the feminine singular, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s used here to denote a specific female person or "lady".</div><div><strong>senhora</strong> This is a formal way to address a woman in Portuguese, equivalent to "madam" or "ma’am" in English. It is respectful and often used with people one does not know well or wishes to show respect towards.</div><div><strong>mora</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "morar", which means "to live" or "to reside". It indicates where someone lives.</div><div><strong>em</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can be translated to "in" or "at" in English, depending on the context. It is used here to indicate location.</div><div><strong>Porto?</strong> This is a proper noun, the name of the second-largest city in Portugal. When using place names, they are capitalized as they are in English and there is no need for a translation.</div>','<h2>A senhora fala português.</h2><div><strong>A</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, here in its feminine singular form. It translates to "the" in English and is used before a feminine noun or title.</div><div><strong>senhora</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "lady" or "madam" when used as a standalone, and also denotes a formal manner to address a woman, similar to "Mrs". in English.</div><div><strong>fala</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "falar", which means "to speak" or "to talk" in English. It agrees with the subject "a senhora".</div><div><strong>português</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "Portuguese", referring to the language. It’s an adjective used here as a noun, denoting what the lady speaks.</div>','<h2>O senhor é muito gentil.</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine nouns and means "the" in English. It’s used here to refer to a specific individual.</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a courteous and formal way to address a man in Portuguese, equivalent to "sir" or "mister" in English. It is a form of respect.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject it is referring to, in this case, "senhor".</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese meaning "very". It’s used to intensify the adjective that follows it.</div><div><strong>gentil</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese meaning "kind" or "gentle". It complements the noun "senhor" to describe his nature. It’s in the masculine singular form to agree with "senhor".</div>','<h2>Vocês estão aprendendo português com o seu computador.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you all" or "you guys" in English. It refers to more than one person being addressed.</div><div><strong>estão</strong> This is the third-person plural of the present tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be". It is used here to indicate a continuous or ongoing action.</div><div><strong>aprendendo</strong> This is the present participle of the verb "aprender", which means "to learn". Combined with "estão" (are), it forms the present continuous tense, "are learning".</div><div><strong>português</strong> This is a noun meaning "Portuguese" and refers to the Portuguese language.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese, equivalent to "with" in English. It indicates the means by which the action is being performed.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s masculine singular to match "computador".</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun meaning "your". In this context, it suggests that the computer belongs to the person or people being addressed.</div><div><strong>computador</strong> This is a noun meaning "computer". It is the object in the sentence, indicating the instrument being used to learn Portuguese.</div>','<h2>Vocês estão sorrindo para a foto.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you all" or "you guys" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and denotes a group of people.</div><div><strong>estão</strong> This is the third-person plural of the present tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be". It describes a temporary state or condition of the subjects (you all/the group).</div><div><strong>sorrindo</strong> This is the present participle or gerund form of the verb "sorrir", which means "to smile". In this sentence, combined with "estão", it describes an action that is currently happening - "are smiling".</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can have several meanings depending on the context. In this sentence, it means "for" indicating the direction or recipient of the smiling.</div><div><strong>a foto</strong> <em>a</em> is the definite article "the", and <em>foto</em> means "photo" in Portuguese. Together, "a foto" means "the photo", which is the object of the sentence that indicates what they are smiling for.</div>','<h2>Vocês trabalham duro.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you all" or "you guys" in English when addressing more than one person.</div><div><strong>trabalham</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "trabalhar", which means "to work". It is used here to agree with the plural subject "vocês".</div><div><strong>duro</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese, equivalent to "hard" in English. It describes the manner in which the work is being done.</div>','<h2>Os senhores são pessoas muito importantes nesta empresa.</h2><div><strong>Os</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine, plural nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>senhores</strong> This is a polite form to address men in Portuguese, usually translated as "sirs" or "gentlemen" in English. It is the plural form of "senhor".</div><div><strong>são</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It is used here to denote a state of being for the subjects "os senhores".</div><div><strong>pessoas</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "people". It is in the plural form, which aligns with the plural article "os" and the verb "são".</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese that means "very". It is used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>importantes</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective in its plural form meaning "important". It qualifies the noun "pessoas", indicating their significance.</div><div><strong>nesta</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "a" (the) which means "in this", referring to the feminine noun "empresa".</div><div><strong>empresa</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "company". It is a feminine singular noun, which is why it uses the feminine singular form of the definite article in "nesta".</div>','<h2>As senhoras viajam pelo mundo todo.</h2><div><strong>As</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine plural nouns, equivalent to "the" in English. It determines the noun "senhoras" in a specific way.</div><div><strong>senhoras</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that translates to "ladies" in English. It is in the plural form, indicating more than one lady.</div><div><strong>viajam</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "viajar", which means "to travel" in English. It indicates that the subject of the sentence is currently traveling.</div><div><strong>pelo</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "por" (by, through, along, for) and the definite article "o" (the) in one masculine singular form. In this context, it means "around" or "throughout" and is used to indicate movement within a broader area.</div><div><strong>mundo</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that translates to "world" in English. It is the direct object of the verb "viajam", indicating where the travel is taking place.</div><div><strong>todo</strong> This word modifies "mundo", meaning "whole" or "entire" in English. It indicates that the travel includes all parts of the world, not just a specific section.</div>','<h2>Os senhores estarão na reunião de negócios amanhã.</h2><div><strong>Os</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, masculine and plural, equivalent to "The" in English. It indicates that we’re talking about specific gentlemen.</div><div><strong>senhores</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "gentlemen". It is used in the plural form to address more than one man and in a formal or polite context.</div><div><strong>estarão</strong> This is a verb in the future tense for the third-person plural in Portuguese, coming from the verb "estar", which means "to be". It indicates an action that will happen in the future, in this case, it’s used to say "will be".</div><div><strong>na</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" and the article "a", translating to "in the" or "at the" in English. It is used to indicate the place where the action of the verb "estarão" is taking place.</div><div><strong>reunião</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "meeting". It is being modified by the following phrase to specify the type of meeting.</div><div><strong>de negócios</strong> This is a phrase that acts as an adjective, qualifying the noun "reunião". It means "business", turning "reunião" into "business meeting".</div><div><strong>amanhã</strong> This is an adverb of time in Portuguese that means "tomorrow". It tells us when the meeting will take place.</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Tu te lembras?</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used informally when addressing someone familiar, such as a friend or a family member.</div><div><strong>te</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese that corresponds to the second-person singular. It is used here to indicate that the action of the verb is directed back to the subject, essentially meaning "yourself".</div><div><strong>lembras?</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "lembrar", which means "to remember" in English. The verb is in the interrogative form, indicating a question is being asked, "Do you remember?"</div>','<h2>Tu te sentas para ler.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used as the subject of the sentence in informal contexts.</div><div><strong>te</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese. It refers back to the subject of the sentence, indicating that the action is being done by the subject to themselves.</div><div><strong>sentas</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "sentar", which means "to sit". Here, it indicates the action of sitting that the subject is performing.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese meaning "for" or "in order to". It’s used to introduce the purpose of the action.</div><div><strong>ler</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "ler", which means "to read". It’s used here to indicate the action that the subject intends to perform after sitting down.</div>','<h2>Hoje, tu estás doente.</h2><div><strong>Hoje</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "today". It denotes the time when the action is taking place or the state is being described.</div><div><strong>tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>estás</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in a temporary sense or state. It describes how the subject is feeling or the state they are in at the moment.</div><div><strong>doente</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "sick" or "ill". Here, it’s used to describe the condition of the subject, which in this case is the person referred to by the pronoun "tu".</div>','<h2>Tu te banhas com água fria.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and indicates the person being spoken to informally.</div><div><strong>te</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese. It refers back to the subject "tu" and means that the subject performs and receives the action of the verb. In English, the equivalent would be "yourself".</div><div><strong>banhas</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "banhar", which means "to bathe". Here, it refers to the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese meaning "with". It is used here to indicate accompaniment or the means by which the action is performed.</div><div><strong>água</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "water". It is the object of the preposition "com" and specifies what the subject uses to bathe.</div><div><strong>fria</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "cold". It describes the temperature of the water. In this context, it must match the feminine, singular form to agree with the noun "água".</div>','<h2>Por que tu choravas?</h2><div><strong>Por que</strong> This is the Portuguese phrase for "why". It’s used to ask for a reason or explanation.</div><div><strong>tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>choravas</strong> This is the second-person singular imperfect tense form of the verb "chorar", which means "to cry". It denotes a repeated or continuous action in the past, similar to "you were crying" or "you used to cry" in English.</div>','<h2>Tu és mecânico de carros.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and is used in an informal context.</div><div><strong>és</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>mecânico</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "mechanic". It refers to a person skilled in repairing machinery, specifically here, it indicates a car mechanic.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition typically meaning "of" or "from". In this context, it is used to link the occupation (mecânico) with the object of specialization (carros).</div><div><strong>carros</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "cars". It’s a plural noun and the object linked to the mechanic’s specialization.</div>','<h2>Agora, tu pegas a faixa da direita.</h2><div><strong>Agora</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "now". It indicates the present time or the immediacy of the action.</div><div><strong>tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s informal and used when speaking to one person who you are familiar with.</div><div><strong>pegas</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "pegar", which means "to take" or "to grab". In this sentence, it can be understood as "you take" or "you grab".</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine nouns, equivalent to the word "the" in English. It specifies which noun you’re talking about.</div><div><strong>faixa</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "lane". It refers to a part of the road or path designated for a specific type of traffic or purpose.</div><div><strong>da</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "de" (of/from) and the feminine article "a" (the). It means "of the" or "from the" and relates to something that belongs to or is part of something else.</div><div><strong>direita</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "right". It’s used here as a noun to indicate the direction or side, as in "right lane".</div>','<h2>Tu preferes ir à direita ou à esquerda?</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used to address someone in an informal way.</div><div><strong>preferes</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "preferir", which means "to prefer". It denotes a preference or choice of the subject being addressed.</div><div><strong>ir</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "ir", which means "to go" in English. In the given sentence, it is used after preferes to indicate the action contemplated by the preference.</div><div><strong>à</strong> This word translates to "to" in English indicating direction towards a place. In Portuguese "à" is a contraction of "a" (to) and the definite article "a" (the), which is used before feminine nouns.</div><div><strong>direita</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "right". It is used here to indicate the direction right as opposed to left.</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This word translates to "or" in English. It is a conjunction used to offer an alternative or choice.</div><div><strong>à</strong> As described previously, this is a contraction in Portuguese meaning "to the".</div><div><strong>esquerda?</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "left". It’s used here to indicate the opposite direction of right, completing the list of options given in the question.</div>','<h2>Tu estás desenhando com um lápis verde.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s informal and used to address someone familiarly.</div><div><strong>estás</strong> This is the second-person singular of the present tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be". It indicates an ongoing action or state.</div><div><strong>desenhando</strong> This is the present participle of the verb "desenhar", which means "to draw". When used with the verb "estar", it forms the present continuous tense, which indicates that the action of drawing is currently in progress.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese, which translates to "with" in English. It’s used here to indicate the instrument being used to perform the action.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is the Portuguese indefinite article for masculine singular nouns, which translates to "a" in English.</div><div><strong>lápis</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese, which means "pencil".</div><div><strong>verde</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "green". It is in the masculine singular form to agree with "lápis".</div>','<h2>Eles são gratos que tu cozinhes o jantar para eles.</h2><div><strong>Eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>são</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>gratos</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "grateful" or "thankful". Here, it’s used in the plural masculine form to agree with the subject "Eles", meaning "they".</div><div><strong>que</strong> This word is a conjunction in Portuguese and can be translated as "that" in English. It’s used here to introduce a subordinate clause explaining what they are thankful for.</div><div><strong>tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" (informal singular) in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>cozinhes</strong> This is the second-person singular present subjunctive tense form of the verb "cozinhar", which means "to cook". The subjunctive mood is used to reflect wishes, hopes, or actions that are not guaranteed to occur.</div><div><strong>o jantar</strong> This is a Portuguese phrase meaning "the dinner". "O" is the masculine singular definite article "the", and "jantar" is a masculine noun meaning "dinner".</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition that means "for" in English. It is used here to indicate the beneficiaries of the action (cooking dinner).</div><div><strong>eles</strong> This is a repetition of the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "them" in English. It’s used here as an object pronoun to represent the beneficiaries of the action.</div>','<h2>O que você recomenda?</h2><div><strong>O que</strong> This is the Portuguese phrase for "what". It is used to start a question regarding the object or action of interest.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and is used here informally to address one person.</div><div><strong>recomenda?</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "recomendar", which means "to recommend". In Portuguese, verbs can be conjugated to agree with the second-person using the third-person form. This verb is used here to inquire about a suggestion or advice.</div>','<h2>Você pratica algum esporte?</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "you" in the context of a conversation. It is a second-person singular subject pronoun.</div><div><strong>pratica</strong> This is the third-person singular present indicative form of the verb "praticar", which means "to practice" or "to play" when referring to sports. Despite being third person, it is used with "você" due to a particularity of Brazilian Portuguese conjugation.</div><div><strong>algum</strong> This is a masculine singular indefinite pronoun meaning "some" or "any". In Portuguese, the pronoun agrees in gender and number with the noun it modifies.</div><div><strong>esporte?</strong> This is a masculine singular noun meaning "sport". It is the object of the verb "pratica", denoting what activity is being practiced or played.</div>','<h2>O que você não entendeu?</h2><div><strong>O que</strong> This is a Portuguese phrase that translates to "What" in English. It is used to start a question about understanding.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the question.</div><div><strong>não</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "not". It negates a part of the sentence, in this case indicating something that was not understood.</div><div><strong>entendeu?</strong> This is the past tense form of the verb "entender", which means "to understand". It’s asking in the second-person singular what the subject did not understand, making it a direct question.</div>','<h2>Você está com o pneu furado!</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be". In this context, it’s conjugated to match the second-person due to "você" being technically a third-person pronoun used for polite address. It describes the state or condition of the subject.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can mean "with" among other meanings. In this sentence, it indicates that the subject is accompanied by or possessing something.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>pneu</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese that means "tire".</div><div><strong>furado</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "furar", which means "to puncture". Here, it serves as an adjective meaning "punctured" or "flat". It matches the masculine singular form to agree with the noun "pneu".</div>','<h2>Você não pode falar com ele?</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>não</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "no" or "not". It negates a statement or a verb.</div><div><strong>pode</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "poder", which means "to be able". In this sentence, it’s in agreement with "você" and translates to "can" or "may".</div><div><strong>falar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to speak" or "to talk" in Portuguese.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This preposition in Portuguese means "with", indicating the association between two parties.</div><div><strong>ele?</strong> This is the third-person singular masculine pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "him" in English. It’s the object of the preposition "com", forming the phrase "with him".</div>','<h2>Você teve uma noite ruim?</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the question.</div><div><strong>teve</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have". In this context, it’s used to ask about the person’s past experience.</div><div><strong>uma</strong> This is a Portuguese indefinite article meaning "a" in English. It is used here before the feminine noun "noite" to indicate one night.</div><div><strong>noite</strong> This is a Portuguese noun for "night". It’s the object of the question, referring to the period being asked about.</div><div><strong>ruim?</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "bad". In the question, it qualifies "noite", asking about the quality of the person’s night.</div>','<h2>Você é muito barulhento.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and is used here to address someone directly.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese, meaning "very" or "a lot". It’s used here to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>barulhento</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "noisy" or "loud". It is in masculine singular form to agree with the subject. If you were describing a female, it would be "barulhenta".</div>','<h2>Você precisa de um envelope?</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here as the subject of the question.</div><div><strong>precisa</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "precisar", which means "to need". In this sentence, it is conjugated to match the second-person singular subject "você".</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese commonly used to indicate necessity or possession, similar to "of" or "from" in English.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is the masculine singular form of an indefinite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English, used here to show an indefinite single quantity.</div><div><strong>envelope?</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese, which means "envelope". It’s the object of the preposition "de" in the question.</div>','<h2>Você sabe qual é o endereço?</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>sabe</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "saber", which means "to know". It is used with "você" due to conjugation rules in Portuguese.</div><div><strong>qual</strong> This translates to "which" or "what" in English. It’s used in questions to inquire about specific information.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense of the verb "ser", which means "to be". It establishes the identity or characteristics of the subject.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes masculine, singular nouns.</div><div><strong>endereço?</strong> This is a Portuguese word meaning "address". It’s the object of the sentence, referring to the location details being inquired about.</div>','<h2>Por que você está nervoso?</h2><div><strong>Por que</strong> This is the Portuguese phrase for "why". It is used to ask the reason for something.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in English. However, when used with "você", it corresponds to the second person. It describes the state or condition of the subject, in this case, being "nervous".</div><div><strong>nervoso</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "nervous". It agrees in gender and number with the person it refers to. If the person were female, it would be "nervosa".</div>','<h2>Você me vendeu um carro.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. In the sentence, it is the subject.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is the first-person singular object pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "me" in English. It indicates that the action of the verb is being done to the speaker.</div><div><strong>vendeu</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "vender", which means "to sell" in Portuguese. Even though "vendeu" appears to refer to the third person, it matches the subject "você", which is used here as second person. This is because, in Portuguese, the second-person formal "você" takes the third-person verb conjugation.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is a masculine singular indefinite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>carro</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "car". It is the direct object of the sentence, receiving the action of the verb.</div>','<h2>Você trabalha em tempo integral?</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the Portuguese subject pronoun for "you" in the singular form. It’s used here to address one person in a formal or informal context.</div><div><strong>trabalha</strong> This is the third-person singular present indicative of the verb "trabalhar", which means "to work" in English. Despite being in the third-person form, it is used with the second-person pronoun "você" due to grammatical conventions in Portuguese.</div><div><strong>em</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition that translates to "in" in English. It’s used to indicate the state or condition of something, like working in a certain mode.</div><div><strong>tempo</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "time". In this context, it refers to the duration or type of work schedule.</div><div><strong>integral</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "full" or "complete". When combined with "tempo", it refers to "full-time", as in working a full schedule or set of hours.</div><div><strong>?</strong> This is the question mark, used at the end of interrogative sentences in Portuguese, as it is in English, to denote that a question is being asked.</div>','<h2>O que você fez hoje?</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article for masculine nouns, equivalent to "the" in English. However, in this context, it’s used as part of the interrogative phrase "o que", which means "what".</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a Portuguese word that means "what" when used in questions. Combined with "O", it forms the interrogative "o que", asking for information or clarification.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fez</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense (preterite) of the verb "fazer", which means "to do" or "to make" in English. It refers to an action that was completed in the past.</div><div><strong>hoje?</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb meaning "today". It refers to the day on which the speaker is asking the question.</div>','<h2> Qual você prefere?</h2><div><strong>Qual</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "which". It is used to introduce a choice or selection among options.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here as the subject of the question.</div><div><strong>prefere?</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "preferir", which means "to prefer". It’s used in the question to ask the preference of the subject "você".</div>','<h2>Como o senhor está hoje?</h2><div><strong>Como</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "how". It is used to start questions about conditions or states.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine nouns, similar to "the" in English. It is used here before the formal second-person singular pronoun "senhor".</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is the formal second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "sir" or the formal "you" in English. It marks a polite or respectful address, mainly used toward men in a formal context.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It is used with "senhor" as a respectful way to say "you are".</div><div><strong>hoje?</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb meaning "today". It specifies the time frame to which the question refers.</div>','<h2>O senhor voa com frequência?</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "sir" or "mister". It’s a formal address for a man, similar to "Mr". in English.</div><div><strong>voa</strong> This is a verb in the third-person singular of the present indicative tense of "voar", which means "to fly". It indicates the action of flying.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that translates to "with" in English.</div><div><strong>frequência?</strong> This is a noun meaning "frequency" in Portuguese. When used in a question, it’s asking about how often something occurs. Here, it is asking about the frequency of flying.</div>','<h2>O senhor tem uma reserva?</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, masculine singular form, meaning "the". It is used before masculine singular nouns and here it is referring to "senhor".</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "sir" or "mister". It is a respectful form of address for a man, similar to "Mr". in English.</div><div><strong>tem</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have" in English. It’s indicating possession or existence of something in this context.</div><div><strong>uma</strong> This is the indefinite article in Portuguese, feminine singular form, meaning "a" or "an" in English. It is used here because the word "reserva" that follows is a feminine noun.</div><div><strong>reserva?</strong> This is a feminine noun in Portuguese meaning "reservation". It is commonly used in the context of booking or reserving something, such as a table at a restaurant or a hotel room. The question mark indicates that this sentence is a question, asking if the gentleman has a reservation.</div>','<h2>O senhor quer a nota fiscal?</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a respectful form of address in Portuguese equivalent to "sir" or "Mr". in English. It is used to respectfully address a man in a formal or polite context.</div><div><strong>quer</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "querer" in Portuguese, which means "to want" or "to wish". In this sentence, it aligns with "senhor" as the subject.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>nota fiscal</strong> This is a compound noun in Portuguese. "Nota" means "note" or "bill", and "fiscal" relates to "fiscal" or "tax". Combined, "nota fiscal" refers to a fiscal document similar to a tax invoice or receipt that records a transaction and is used for tax purposes in Brazil and other Portuguese-speaking regions.</div><div><strong>?</strong> This punctuation mark indicates that the sentence is a question.</div>','<h2>O senhor não iria muito longe!</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "sir" or "mister". It is a formal way to address a man and is often used as a polite form of address.</div><div><strong>não</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "no" or "not". It negates a statement or responds negatively to a question.</div><div><strong>iria</strong> This is the conditional tense of the verb "ir", which means "to go". In this case, it translates to "would go" in English.</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese meaning "very" or "a lot". It’s used here to modify the extent of how far the subject would go.</div><div><strong>longe</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese that means "far". It indicates the distance one would or wouldn’t go.</div>','<h2>O senhor sabe onde fica a praia?</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine nouns in the singular form, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "sir" or "mister". It is often used as a formal and polite way to address a man.</div><div><strong>sabe</strong> This comes from the verb "saber" in Portuguese, which means "to know". "Sabe" is the third-person singular present tense form, so it translates to "knows" in English — in this context, it is used for the second-person singular as a formal address.</div><div><strong>onde</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb meaning "where". It is used in questions to ask about the location of something.</div><div><strong>fica</strong> This comes from the verb "ficar" in Portuguese, which means "to be located" or "to stay". "Fica" is the third-person singular present tense form, and here it translates to "is located" or "is" when asking about location.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine nouns in the singular form, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>praia</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "beach".</div>','<h2>O senhor pode ligar de novo mais tarde?</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, masculine singular form, corresponding to "the" in English. It precedes the masculine noun or title it’s referring to.</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "sir" or "mister". It is a respectful form of address for a man, often used in formal situations.</div><div><strong>pode</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "poder" in the present indicative, which means "can" or "may" in English. It expresses the ability or permission to perform an action.</div><div><strong>ligar</strong> This is the infinitive form of a Portuguese verb that means "to call" or "to connect" in English. In this sentence, it refers to making a phone call.</div><div><strong>de novo</strong> This Portuguese phrase means "again" or "once more" in English. It suggests repeating an action.</div><div><strong>mais tarde?</strong> This is a phrase combining "mais" meaning "more" and "tarde" meaning "late" in Portuguese. Together, they mean "later", referring to some time in the future.</div>','<h2>O senhor tem muita paciência.</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article for "the", used here in the masculine singular form. It precedes masculine singular nouns or adjectives.</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "sir" or "mister". It is used as a respectful form of address for a man, similar to "Mr". in English. In this sentence, it’s the subject.</div><div><strong>tem</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have" in English. It concurs with the subject "O senhor".</div><div><strong>muita</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "a lot of" or "much". It’s an indefinite quantity adjective and modifies the noun "paciência".</div><div><strong>paciência</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "patience". It’s the object of the sentence, indicating what the subject "has a lot of".</div>','<h2>O senhor tem que trabalhar agora.</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article "the" in Portuguese, used here to address someone formally or respectfully.</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This word means "sir" in Portuguese. It is a respectful term of address for a man, often equivalent to "Mr". in English.</div><div><strong>tem</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have" in Portuguese. In this context, it is used with "que" to express the obligation "has to".</div><div><strong>que</strong> This word is commonly used in Portuguese to indicate obligation or necessity, "that" or in constructions for "to have to" do something. In the sentence, "tem que" forms the expression "has to".</div><div><strong>trabalhar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "trabalhar", which means "to work" in Portuguese.</div><div><strong>agora</strong> This is an adverb meaning "now" in Portuguese. It indicates that the action of working should happen at the present moment.</div>','<h2>O senhor já escolheu o prato principal?</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, meaning "the", and is used here to refer to a specific noun. It matches the masculine singular form to agree with the noun it precedes.</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a respectful form of address in Portuguese equivalent to "sir" or "mister" in English. It denotes formal or polite address to an adult male.</div><div><strong>já</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese meaning "already". It indicates that an action may have taken place by now or before the present moment.</div><div><strong>escolheu</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "escolher", which means "to choose". It indicates that the action of choosing was possibly completed in the past.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article again, meaning "the", here used a second time to refer to another specific noun that follows. It matches the masculine singular form to agree with this following noun as well.</div><div><strong>prato</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "dish" or "plate". It refers to a particular course in a meal, in this case paired with an adjective to specify the type of course.</div><div><strong>principal</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese meaning "main" or "principal", qualifying the noun "prato" to indicate it is the main dish of a meal.</div><div>The sentence as a whole, "O senhor já escolheu o prato principal?" translates to "Has the gentleman already chosen the main dish?" or "Have you (formally addressed) already chosen the main dish?" in English. It is used by waitstaff in restaurants to inquire if a male customer has made a decision regarding his meal choice.</div>','<h2>Tudo bem. Em que o senhor está interessado?</h2><div><strong>Tudo bem</strong> This is a common Portuguese greeting which translates to "All good" or "Is everything fine?" in English. It can be used both as a question and a statement.</div><div><strong>Em</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that translates to "in" or "on" in English. It’s used here to start a question about interest.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "what" when used in questions. It’s inquiring about the subject of interest.</div><div><strong>o senhor</strong> This is a respectful form of address in Portuguese, equivalent to "sir" or the formal "you" (second-person singular) in English. It is used to politely address a man in a formal context.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "estar" in the present tense, meaning "is" in English. It is used here with "o senhor" (he/she/you formal) to form the present continuous structure.</div><div><strong>interessado</strong> This is a past participle adjective in Portuguese meaning "interested". When used with the verb "estar", it forms the present continuous tense to express a current state of interest. It is in masculine singular form to agree with "o senhor".</div>','<h2>O senhor pode descansar, está muito tarde.</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It defines "senhor" as a specific gentleman or sir.</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "sir" or "mister". It’s a formal address for a man.</div><div><strong>pode</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "poder", which means "to be able to" or "can". It indicates the ability or permission to perform the action that follows.</div><div><strong>descansar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "descansar", which means "to rest". Here, it’s the action that the "senhor" can perform.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be". It describes the state or condition of being of the subject or the current situation.</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This is an adverb that means "very" in English. It’s used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>tarde</strong> This is an adjective that means "late" in English. When combined with "muito", it communicates that it is very late in terms of time.</div>','<h2>O senhor vai à sua reunião.</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine, singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes male-gendered nouns or pronouns.</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a respectful form of address in Portuguese, equivalent to "sir" or "mister" in English. In this sentence, it is the subject being referred to.</div><div><strong>vai</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "ir" in the present indicative tense, meaning "goes" or "is going". Here, it indicates the action that the subject ("o senhor") is undertaking.</div><div><strong>à</strong> This is a contraction in Portuguese that merges the preposition "a" meaning "to", with the definite article "a" meaning "the", used here because "reunião" is a feminine noun. Together they form "à", which translates to "to the" in English.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "your" in a formal context or "his/her" depending on the context. It agrees in gender and number with the noun it modifies, which in this case is "reunião".</div><div><strong>reunião</strong> This is a feminine noun in Portuguese meaning "meeting". It is the object of the verb and is where "o senhor" is going.</div>','<h2>A senhora pode pagar no caixa.</h2><div><strong>A</strong> This is a definite article in Portuguese, "the" in English. It’s feminine singular to accord with "senhora".</div><div><strong>senhora</strong> This word means "lady" or "madam" in Portuguese. It’s a polite form of address for a woman, similar to "Mrs". or "Ms". in English.</div><div><strong>pode</strong> This is a verb form of "poder", which means "can" or "to be able to". In this case, "pode" is the third-person singular present indicative, meaning "can" or "is able to".</div><div><strong>pagar</strong> This is an infinitive verb meaning "to pay" in Portuguese. It remains in the base form here as it follows modal verbs like "pode".</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "o" (the). In this context, it translates to "at the" in English.</div><div><strong>caixa</strong> This means "cashier" or "checkout". It refers to the physical place where payments are made, such as a cash register or payment counter.</div>','<h2>Ah! E aonde a senhora quer ir?</h2><div><strong>Ah!</strong> This is an interjection in Portuguese that expresses a range of emotions, such as realization, relief, or surprise, similar to the English "ah!" or "oh!".</div><div><strong>E</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect words, phrases, or clauses within a sentence.</div><div><strong>aonde</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb of place that means "to where" or "where to". It is used when asking or talking about destinations or directions.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the Portuguese feminine definite article, equivalent to "the" in English. It also implies politeness in this context when referring to "senhora".</div><div><strong>senhora</strong> This is a formal Portuguese term for "lady" or "madam" and is used as a respectful form of address for a woman. It is similar to "Mrs". or "Ms". in English.</div><div><strong>quer</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "querer", which means "to want" in Portuguese. It indicates a desire or intention.</div><div><strong>ir</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "ir", which means "to go" in Portuguese. It indicates the action of going or moving from one place to another.</div>','<h2>A senhora deixou a placa na porta...</h2><div><strong>A</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article for the feminine singular, similar to "the" in English. It precedes a feminine noun.</div><div><strong>senhora</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "lady" or "madam". It is a respectful form of address for a woman, similar to "Mrs". in English.</div><div><strong>deixou</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "deixar", which means "to leave" or "to let". Here, it indicates that the lady has left something behind.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is another occurrence of the Portuguese definite article for the feminine singular, again meaning "the".</div><div><strong>placa</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "plate", "sign", or "plaque" in English. In the context of this sentence, it likely refers to a sign.</div><div><strong>na</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (meaning "in" or "on") and the definite article "a" (feminine singular), translating to "on the" or "in the" in English.</div><div><strong>porta</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "door".</div><div>... (ellipsis) In writing, an ellipsis indicates that the sentence is incomplete or that the speaker’s thought trails off.</div>','<h2>Que tipo de quarto a senhora deseja?</h2><div><strong>Que</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "what". It is used to start a question about choice or preference.</div><div><strong>tipo</strong> This Portuguese word means "type" or "kind". It is asking about a variety, category, or sort.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition that in this context means "of" or "about", indicating a relation to the subject, in this case, a relation to "quarto" (room).</div><div><strong>quarto</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "room". Here, it is the subject of the sentence and the term being queried about.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article "the" in Portuguese when used before a feminine noun or, in this case, part of a formal address for a woman. It typically precedes "senhora" as a sign of respect.</div><div><strong>senhora</strong> This is a formal address in Portuguese equivalent to "madam" or "lady" in English. The sentence is using a formal tone, addressing the person politely.</div><div><strong>deseja</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the Portuguese verb "desejar", which means "to wish" or "to want". In this sentence, it’s asking about the lady’s preference or choice.</div>','<h2>Olá! Aonde a senhora gostaria de ir?</h2><div><strong>Olá!</strong> This is a common Portuguese greeting equivalent to "Hello!" or "Hi!" in English.</div><div><strong>Aonde</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb of place, equivalent to "where" in English when indicating direction. It asks about the destination of someone.</div><div><strong>a senhora</strong> This phrase combines the definite article "a" (the) and the noun "senhora" (lady, Mrs., or ma’am), used to address a woman formally and respectfully.</div><div><strong>gostaria</strong> This is the third-person singular conditional tense of the verb "gostar", which means "to like" or "would like". It is used to express a polite desire or preference.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition that translates to "of" or "from" in English. It is used here to connect the verb "gostaria" with the following verb, forming a more complete idea of preference.</div><div><strong>ir</strong> This is the Portuguese verb "to go". In this sentence, it’s used in the infinitive form, implying the action of going somewhere.</div>','<h2>A senhora está procurando mais alguma coisa?</h2><div><strong>A</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English. It is used here to refer to "senhora", which is a respectful form of address for a woman.</div><div><strong>senhora</strong> This is a noun meaning "lady" or "Mrs". in Portuguese. It’s a formal way to address a woman and is equivalent to "Madam" in English.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It is used to denote temporary states, locations, or ongoing actions.</div><div><strong>procurando</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "procurar", which means "to look for" or "to search". The gerund form is used here to indicate an ongoing action.</div><div><strong>mais</strong> This word translates to "more" in English. It can indicate an additional quantity or further extent of something.</div><div><strong>alguma</strong> This word means "some" or "any" in Portuguese, indicating an indefinite quantity or possibility.</div><div><strong>coisa?</strong> This is a noun that means "thing" in Portuguese. In questions, it often refers to something nonspecific or unknown by the speaker.</div>','<h2>Vocês têm um cachorro bonito.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>têm</strong> This is the second-person plural of the present tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have" in English. It indicates possession.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is the indefinite article in Portuguese, used here in the masculine singular form, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>cachorro</strong> This Portuguese word means "dog". It is a masculine singular noun being described in the sentence.</div><div><strong>bonito</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "beautiful" or "pretty" in English. It is in the masculine singular form, agreeing with the noun "cachorro".</div>','<h2>Vocês querem fazer um bolo.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "you" when addressing more than one person or in a formal singular context. It is a pronoun used here as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>querem</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "querer", which means "to want". In this sentence, it is used to express a desire to do something, applying to "vocês".</div><div><strong>fazer</strong> This is an infinitive verb in Portuguese, which translates to "to make" or "to do" in English. It’s placed after "querem" to indicate the action that "vocês" want to perform.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is a Portuguese article equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It’s an indefinite article used here to introduce a singular, masculine noun.</div><div><strong>bolo</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "cake". It’s a common noun denoting the item that "vocês" want to make. It agrees in gender and number with the preceding article "um".</div>','<h2>Incrível! Vocês têm uma garagem?</h2><div><strong>Incrível!</strong> This is a Portuguese word for "amazing" or "incredible". It expresses surprise or admiration.</div><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you all" or "you guys" in English, addressing more than one person.</div><div><strong>têm</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have". It agrees with "vocês" in number and person.</div><div><strong>uma</strong> This is the Portuguese indefinite article for feminine singular nouns, meaning "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>garagem?</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "garage". It is a feminine singular noun, so it matches with the article "uma". It’s used here in a question.</div>','<h2>Vocês escreviam uma carta.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you [all]" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and is used to address more than one person.</div><div><strong>escreviam</strong> This is the second-person plural imperfect tense form of the verb "escrever", which means "to write". It indicates an action that was ongoing or habitual in the past.</div><div><strong>uma</strong> This is an indefinite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "a" in English. It is used here in the feminine form to match the gender of the noun it introduces.</div><div><strong>carta</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "letter". It is feminine and singular, and it is the direct object of the sentence, receiving the action of the verb "escrever".</div>','<h2>Certo. O que vocês têm para beber?</h2><div><strong>Certo</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "right" or "correct". It is often used as an affirmative answer that means "Sure" or "Okay".</div><div><strong>O que</strong> This is a Portuguese phrase that means "What". It is a question word used to inquire about something.</div><div><strong>vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you all" or "you guys" in English. It’s the subject of the question.</div><div><strong>têm</strong> This is the third-person plural form of the verb "ter" in Portuguese, which means "to have". It is used here to ask about what kind of drinks are available (they have).</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that means "for". In this context, it’s used to indicate the purpose of what is being asked about (to drink).</div><div><strong>beber</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to drink" in Portuguese. It refers to the action of drinking in the question.</div>','<h2>Vocês deveriam tomar um banho.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>deveriam</strong> This is the second-person plural past imperfect subjunctive of the verb "dever", which means "should" or "ought to". It indicates a suggestion or an unrealized condition in the past.</div><div><strong>tomar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "tomar", which means "to take" or "to have" in the context of consuming food, drinks, or in this case, taking a shower or bath.</div><div><strong>um banho</strong> This is a masculine singular noun phrase consisting of the indefinite article "um" (a) and the noun "banho" (bath or shower). The phrase means "a bath" or "a shower".</div>','<h2>Vocês estão esperando o trem.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you all" or "you guys" in English. It indicates that the speaker is addressing a group of people.</div><div><strong>estão</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It is used here to indicate a continuous or ongoing action by the subjects of the sentence.</div><div><strong>esperando</strong> This is the present participle of the verb "esperar", which means "to wait" in Portuguese. Combined with "estão", it forms the present continuous tense, translating to "are waiting" in English.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>trem</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese, which translates to "train" in English. It’s the object of the sentence, indicating what the subjects are waiting for.</div>','<h2>Vocês estudaram muito o dia todo.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you all" or "you guys" in English. It is used as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>estudaram</strong> This is the second-person plural past tense form of the verb "estudar", which means "to study". It indicates that the action was completed in the past.</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese meaning "a lot" or "much". It describes the intensity or degree of the action of the verb "estudaram".</div><div><strong>o dia todo</strong> This phrase combines the definite article "o" (the), the noun "dia" (day), and the adjective "todo" (whole, entire). Put together, it translates to "the whole day" or "all day long", indicating the duration of the studying.</div>','<h2>Vocês vão à praia frequentemente.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person.</div><div><strong>vão</strong> This is the third-person plural of the present indicative tense of the verb "ir", which means "to go". In this sentence, it’s used with "vocês" and means "you go".</div><div><strong>à</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "a" (to) and the definite article "a" (the), making "à". In Portuguese, prepositions sometimes merge with articles to form a single word. It is used here to create the phrase "à praia" which means "to the beach".</div><div><strong>praia</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "beach".</div><div><strong>frequentemente</strong> This is an adverb meaning "frequently" or "often". It describes the frequency with which an action is performed.</div>','<h2>Vocês beberam café esta manhã.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person.</div><div><strong>beberam</strong> This is the third-person plural past tense form of the verb "beber", which means "to drink". In this sentence, it’s conjugated to match the second-person plural subject "vocês".</div><div><strong>café</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "coffee".</div><div><strong>esta</strong> This word is a demonstrative adjective in Portuguese meaning "this". It is used here to indicate a time period (morning) that is close to the speaker in time.</div><div><strong>manhã</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "morning". It refers to the time of day.</div>','<h2>Vocês são estudantes universitários.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>são</strong> This is the third-person plural of the present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>estudantes</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "students". It is used here in the plural form to denote more than one person who is attending an educational institution.</div><div><strong>universitários</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "university". Here, it’s used in its plural masculine form to describe the type of students. It agrees in gender and number with the noun it describes, "estudantes". If it were describing a feminine subject, it would be "universitárias".</div>','<h2>Vocês acabaram de correr a maratona.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you all" or "you guys" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>acabaram</strong> This is the third-person plural past tense for the verb "acabar", which means "to finish" or "to end". In this context, it’s used with "de" to indicate the action has just occurred.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This preposition is used here as part of the construction "acabar de + infinitive" which is used to indicate that something has just happened.</div><div><strong>correr</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "correr", which means "to run". In this sentence, it’s connected with "acabar de" to indicate the recent completion of the action.</div><div><strong>a maratona</strong> This phrase is composed of the definite article "a", which is feminine singular to match the feminine noun "maratona", meaning "the marathon". This indicates the specific event that they have just completed running.</div>','<h2>Vocês nadaram na piscina o dia todo.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you all" or "you guys" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and is used to address more than one person informally.</div><div><strong>nadaram</strong> This is the third-person plural past tense form of the verb "nadar", which means "to swim". It indicates that the action was performed by the subjects in the past.</div><div><strong>na</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the article "a" (the) in Portuguese, equivalent to "in the" in English. It’s used here to specify the location where the action took place.</div><div><strong>piscina</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "pool". It’s a feminine singular noun and is the object of the preposition "na", stating where the action of swimming took place.</div><div><strong>o dia todo</strong> This phrase means "all day" in English. "O" is the masculine article "the", "dia" means "day", and "todo" means "all" or "whole". Together, they indicate the duration of the swimming activity.</div>','<h2>Vocês entenderão a situação.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person.</div><div><strong>entenderão</strong> This is the future tense third-person plural form of the verb "entender", which means "to understand". In this sentence, it refers to the action that "you" (vocês) will do.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, used here for the feminine singular noun that follows, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>situação</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "situation". Here, it’s the object of the sentence, representing the thing that will be understood.</div>','<h2>Vocês querem comprar três passagens.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>querem</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "querer", which means "to want". In this sentence, it is conjugated to agree with the subject "vocês", indicating that a group of people want something.</div><div><strong>comprar</strong> This is an infinitive verb in Portuguese that means "to buy". It is used here after the verb "querem" to express what the subject wishes to do.</div><div><strong>três</strong> This is a numerical adjective in Portuguese and it means "three". It indicates the quantity of the item the subjects want to buy.</div><div><strong>passagens</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese, which means "tickets" or "passages" in English. In this sentence, it refers to tickets that the group wants to purchase.</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);